docs.abstract: President Trump wants unauthorized immigrants and asylum seekers deported “with no Judges or Court Cases.” What due-process rights do migrants have?
docs.snippet: President Trump wants unauthorized immigrants and asylum seekers deported “with no Judges or Court Cases.” What due-process rights do migrants have?
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said on Twitter this weekend that undocumented immigrants were invaders who “must immediately, with no Judges or Court Cases,” be sent home. Mr. Trump’s comments prompted criticism that he wanted the United States to strip immigrants and asylum seekers of due-process rights. He also appeared to ignore the fact that some people who enter the country illegally are already removed from the United States without court hearings.

headline.main: Due Process for Undocumented Immigrants, Explained
headline.print_headline: Migrants to the U.S. Are Entitled to Due Process, With Some Exceptions

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — More than 35 people were charged with selling drugs on the so-called dark web, the Justice Department announced on Tuesday, marking the first time that federal prosecutors made the sellers of illegal goods their primary focus rather than the operators of illicit online marketplaces.

headline.main: Drug Dealers Targeted in Sweep of Illicit Online Marketplaces
headline.print_headline: Shift in Tactics Targets  Sellers, Not Online Sites, In Corner of Dark Web

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Calling Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials “American heroes,” Vice President Mike Pence doubled down on the Trump administration’s defense of the maligned agency on Friday and demanded that Democrats end their “irresponsible” push to disband it.

docs.abstract: Two months after four American soldiers were killed in the West African country, a group of Green Berets and local forces killed 11 ISIS militants in a previously undisclosed battle.
docs.snippet: Two months after four American soldiers were killed in the West African country, a group of Green Berets and local forces killed 11 ISIS militants in a previously undisclosed battle.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Green Berets working with government forces in Niger killed 11 Islamic State militants in a firefight in December, the American military acknowledged for the first time on Wednesday. The battle occurred two months after four United States soldiers died in an ambush in another part of Niger — and after senior commanders had imposed stricter limits on military missions in the West African country.

headline.main: U.S. Kept Silent About Its Role in Another Firefight in Niger
headline.print_headline: ISIS Struck G.I.s Again in Niger, But U.S. Kept Quiet About Battle
